title: feedback- no grade yet
body: Strengths:+ Nicely done.+ 74 respondents in your survey? Well done.+ Good use of graphics.+ Finished before deadline! Not-so-strong points:+ References should be inline with the names of the people being referenced.To make references:+ create a `myrefs.bib` file.+ add `\bibliographystyle{plain} \bibliography{myrefs} \end{document}` to the _end_ of your file.+ Place some bibtex entries in your `myrefs.bib` file.     + Pro tip: If you got to many on-line bibliography servers, there is often a "bibtext" button; e.g        right-hand-side, yellow box, see "export formats" with "bibtex" underneath![image](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/29195/12721290/1499f4ee-c8cd-11e5-9506-6f0a52814631.png)Bibtext entries have labels. For example, the following entry has the label `mh:icse:09`.```@inproceedings{mh:icse:09,  author    = {Emerson R. Murphy{-}Hill and               Chris Parnin and               Andrew P. Black},  title     = {How we refactor, and how we know it},  booktitle = {31st International Conference on Software Engineering, {ICSE} 2009,               May 16-24, 2009, Vancouver, Canada, Proceedings},  pages     = {287--297},  year      = {2009},   url       = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1109/ICSE.2009.5070529},  doi       = {10.1109/ICSE.2009.5070529}, }```To insert this into the article somewhere in the body text, use `\cite{mh:icse:09}`.
